{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:33:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:33:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17397"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.12,0.16,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10087"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55786"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10416"},{"type":"tags","id":"10437"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23617"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe occipital lobe contains specialised regions for processing visual information received from the retina via the optic radiation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of the primary visual cortex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcarine sulcus of the occipital lobe","Lingual gyrus of the occipital lobe","Lateral surface of the occipital lobe","Cuneus of the occipital lobe","Occipital pole"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcarine sulcus of the occipital lobe\u003C/strong\u003E contains the primary visual cortex (V1). This area receives direct input from the lateral geniculate nucleus via the optic radiation and is organised in a retinotopic manner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elingual gyrus of the occipital lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is located on the inferior surface of the occipital lobe, below the calcarine sulcus. While it plays a role in visual processing, particularly color recognition and processing of letters, it is part of the secondary visual cortex (V2).\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral surface of the occipital lobe\u003C/strong\u003E contains visual areas V2, V3, V4, and V5, which are responsible for processing complex visual features like motion, color, and form, but not primary visual processing.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecuneus of the occipital lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is a wedge-shaped area on the medial surface of the occipital lobe, located between the calcarine sulcus and the parieto-occipital sulcus. It is involved in basic visual processing but is not the site of V1.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital pole\u003C/strong\u003E is the most posterior portion of the occipital lobe. While it is near the primary visual cortex, V1 is specifically located within the calcarine sulcus rather than at the pole itself.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary visual cortex is organised such that the upper visual field is represented below the calcarine sulcus and the lower visual field above it. The central visual field has proportionally more cortical representation than the peripheral visual field.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary visual cortex (V1) is located in the calcarine sulcus of the occipital lobe.","The occipital lobe processes visual information in a retinotopic manner, with the upper visual field represented below the calcarine sulcus and lower visual field above.","The central visual field has a larger cortical representation than the peripheral visual field."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake R. Gray\u2019s Atlas of Anatomy. 3rd ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021.","Vivekananda U. Neurology. 5th edition. Elsevier; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55786"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17397"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55786"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T16:45:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T16:48:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10087"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app